Bayesian modeling and prediction for movies

Setup

Load packages

library(ggplot2)

library(statsr)
library(BAS)
load("movies.Rdata")

Part 1: Data

The data is randomly sampled . 651 random samples of movies produced and released before 2016 were taken and they were augmented with ratings information from IMDB and Rotten Tomatoes . I can generalize the inferences made from this dataset to all movies that were produced and released before 2016 .

The data is not randomly assigned . There is no notion of treatment and control groups , this is only an observational study . Hence causal analysis is not possible .

Reservations : It is very likely that not all movies produced and released would have had reviews in rotten tomatoes and imdb , it isn’t very clear if the data was chosen from a subset that had such reviews , if this is case then the generalization would be good only if that number of movies not covered by such sites is small .

movies <- mutate(movies,feature_film=factor(ifelse(title_type == "Feature Film","yes","no"),levels = c("yes","no")),drama = factor(ifelse(genre == "Drama","yes","no"),levels =c("yes","no")),mpaa_rating_R = factor(ifelse(mpaa_rating == "R","yes","no"),levels =c("yes","no")),oscar_season = factor(ifelse(thtr_rel_month <= 12 & thtr_rel_month >=10,"yes","no"),levels =c("yes","no")),summer_season = factor(ifelse(thtr_rel_month>=5 & thtr_rel_month<=8,"yes","no"),levels =c("yes","no")))

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

I will be bucketing the audience score in 11 buckets/classes for plotting purposes . A scoring class of 6 for ex corresponds to a rating between 60-70%

#bucketing audience score in 11 levels
movies_subset<- mutate(movies_subset,scoring_class = as.factor(as.integer(movies$audience_score / 10)))

Narrative :

Approximately 90.8%(591 entries) of the movies in the dataset are classified as feature_films , hence one needs to contrast the audience score of non feature films with the audience score show above .

Non feature films have a much higher average rating compared to their feature film counterparts and this variable will have a significant impact on the final model

The score distribution for non feature film is roughly concentrated around 80% with a very long and extremely light left tail . This can either indicate outliers or the presence of another variable that has a higher wt/significance than this one .

Part 4: Modeling

Our goal is to create a parsimonious model with a resonable goodness of fit .

I will be using MCMC since the model space is very large to study a model with all parameters.

movies_subset_for_modelling <- subset(movies,select = c("audience_score","feature_film","drama","runtime","mpaa_rating_R","thtr_rel_year","oscar_season","summer_season","imdb_rating","imdb_num_votes","critics_score","best_pic_nom","best_pic_win","best_actor_win","best_actress_win","best_dir_win","top200_box"))

movies_bas = bas.lm(audience_score ~ ., movies_subset_for_modelling,prior = "BIC",method = "MCMC")
## Warning in bas.lm(audience_score ~ ., movies_subset_for_modelling, prior =
## "BIC", : dropping 1 rows due to missing data
plot(movies_bas,which = 1 )

plot(movies_bas,which = 4 )

I see that the residual plot suggest a huge number of outlier and hence the BMA model is questionable .

I know that having correlated variables tend to dampen the inclusion probabilities of other important variables so let us try removing imdb_rating as it contributes the most to the current model and run the diagnostics again .

movies_bas = bas.lm(audience_score ~ .- imdb_rating ,movies_subset_for_modelling,prior = "BIC",method = "MCMC")
## Warning in bas.lm(audience_score ~ . - imdb_rating,
## movies_subset_for_modelling, : dropping 1 rows due to missing data
diagnostics(movies_bas)
## Warning in if (type == "pip") {: the condition has length > 1 and only the
## first element will be used

plot(movies_bas,which = 1 , add.smooth = "F")

plot(movies_bas,which = 2 )

plot(movies_bas,which = 3 )

plot(movies_bas,which = 4 )

From the above plots I notice the spread of the residuals is not uniform across the range of fitted values , leading us to believe the bma model is not good for prediction .

I also notice that a very small fraction of the sample space was discovered and the cumulative probability quickly tends to 1 .

I also get the highest bayes factor for a 4 predictor model .

The highest inclusion probability is for critics_score , runtime , feature_film , imdb_num_votes .

The goal of this whole exercise is to develop a model that would best predict the audience_score / popularity . So under this context I need to choose the BPM model , Let us now look at the coefficients of the best predicitive model

BPM = predict(movies_bas, estimator="BPM")
(movies_bas$namesx[attr(BPM$fit, 'model') +1])[-1]
## [1] "feature_filmno" "imdb_num_votes" "critics_score"
movies_coef = coef(movies_bas)
movies_frame = data.frame(cbind(movies_coef$conditionalmeans[BPM$best,],movies_coef$conditionalsd[BPM$best,]),row.names = movies_coef$namesx)
colnames(movies_frame) = c("conditional_mean","conditional_std")

The best predictive model consists of of only 3 predictors feature_film , critics_score , imdb_num_voes

This also happens to be the Median probability model as it consists of predictors having inclusion probabilities over 0.5

The coefficient of imdb_num_votes suggest that the model is sensitive to movies with high number of votes , this makes sense as a lower number of votes do signify a lower popularity in terms of reach .

Part 5: Prediction

I will be using the BPM model developed in the previous section to predict the audience_score of Captain America : Civil War(20160.

Our model only depends on feature_film , imdb_num_votes and critics_score since this was the BPM .

small_predictive_model = bas.lm(audience_score ~ feature_film + imdb_num_votes + critics_score,movies_subset_for_modelling,prior = "BIC")

new_vector = data.frame(audience_score = 89 , feature_film = "yes",critics_score=90,imdb_num_votes = 377545)
new_vector$feature_film = factor(new_vector$feature_film,levels = c("yes","no"))
prediction = predict(small_predictive_model,newdata = new_vector, estimator="BPM",se.fit = TRUE )

prediction$Ybma

Part 6: Conclusion

Predicting movie popularity is not trivial .

The model is conservative when it comes to predicting popularity and going by the residual plots the model may be good in the low popularity range .

We arrived at a model with feature_film , critics_score and num_votes but other seemingly important factors like best_pic_nom , best_actor_win etc received very low inclusion probabilities which I believe is partly due to the low percentage of observations for those cases i.e a more accurate model could have been developed if we had more observations .

Other data points that would have made a good addition to the dataset would be the number of critics that reviewed a movie , it gives a credibility to the score and the number of awards the specific movie won , it could increase its popularity later by fueling DVD sales .
